Tradeoff (Latency, Througput, Availability, Consistency)

- Latency (how fast a write/read returns)
- Throughput (how many ops/sec system handles)
- Availability (system keeps serving even under failure)
- Consistency (how “correct / up-to-date” data is)

1) Log tracking

    Client → leader → append log → followers pull (or leader pushes) → followers update

    Latency        Low to Medium                Leader returns fast; replication happens async or batched
    Througput      Very High                    Sequential writes + batching + no coordination per follower ack
    Availability   High                         leader can accept writes even if followers lag temporarily
    Consistency    Eventual/weak until ack      async(follower lag exists) and Sync(data loss if leader crashes)
    OptmisiedFor   Throughput + availability
    Cost           Low cost per write

2) Consensus

    Client → leader → followers → majority ack → commit → reply

    Latency            High              Majority round-trip required
    Througput          Low–Medium        Coordination bottleneck
    Availability       Medium            Needs majority alive
    Consistency        Strong
    OptmisiedFor       Correctness + consistency
    Cost               Network + coordination 

3) Versioning

    Client writes to any node with timestamp/vector clock
    Reads from multiple nodes → detect conflict → resolve client-side

    Latency           Very Low 
    Througput         Very High
    Availability      Very High
    Consistency       Eventual
    OptmisiedFor      Availability + low latency
    Cost              Low write cost, higher read/conflict cost

4) Repair (Anti Entropy)

    Writes go to any replica → background repair syncs inconsistencies

    Latency          Low (writes), Medium (reads with repair)
    Througput        High (no sync on write)
    Availability     Very High
    Consistency      Eventual
    OptmisiedFor     Scalability + availability
    Cost             Background repair cost (CPU + network over time)

5) High Watermark

    Leader tracks ISR (in-sync replicas)
    High Watermark = highest offset replicated to majority ISR

    Latency          Medium (wait for replication threshold)
    Througput        High (append-only logs, batching)
    Availability     Medium–High (depends on ISR health)
    Consistency      Strong for committed data
    OptmisiedFor     Safe ordered streaming
    Cost             Moderate cost (coordination + tracking ISR state)

6) Client-controlled Consistency Levels

    One
    Latency          Very Low
    Througput        Very High
    Availability     Very High
    Consistency      Weak
    OptmisiedFor     Speed + Cost
    Cost             Lowest cost
    Why              No coordination

    QUORUM
    Latency          Medium
    Througput        Medium
    Availability     Medium–High (depends on ISR health)
    Consistency      Strong-ish
    OptmisiedFor     balance
    Cost             Medium cost

    ALL
    Latency          High
    Througput        Low
    Availability     Low
    Consistency      Strong
    OptmisiedFor     Correctness
    Cost             Highest cost


================================================================================================================

Async log → cheapest + fastest
Consensus → most expensive + most correct
Versioning → cheap writes, expensive reconciliation
Anti-entropy → pushes cost to background
Quorum → balanced cost vs correctness tradeoff

=================================================================================================================


1) Classify the system based on functional requirements, 
2) Choose the consistency model based on correctness vs availability tradeoff, 
3) Finally pick a replication strategy that implements that consistency efficiently

================================================================================================================

1) Do I need correctness above all? 
      YES → Consensus (Raft/Paxos)
2) Do I need global availability with tolerance to conflicts?
      YES → Versioning + Anti-entropy
3) Do I need high throughput event stream? 
      YES → Log replication + High watermark
4) Do I need tunable consistency?
      YES → Quorum-based system (Dynamo/Cassandra style)

==============================================================================================================

1) Kafka (Log system with bounded consistency)
      Optimized for: Throughput + Ordered durable stream
      Log Replication + ISR + High Watermark

2) Cassandra (Availability-first KV with tunable consistency)
      Optimized for: Availability + Scalability with eventual consistency
      Versioning + Anti-entropy + Tunable Quorum

3) Google Spanner (Consensus + global ordering = strongest consistency)
      Optimized for: Global strong consistency
      Consensus (Paxos) + Synchronous replication + TrueTime

4) Dynamo (Availability-first KV with conflict resolution)
      Optimized for: Availability-first distributed storage
      Versioning + Anti-entropy + Quorum tuning

5) Distributed (Consensus-backed replicated log system)
      Optimized for: Correctness + Decent throughput
      Consensus + Replicated log + Quorum reads/writes




    

  
